# SEO Optimization Standards

Treat SEO as a first-class priority during the development of any task. These rules ensure high search engine visibility and performance.

<rule>
name: seo_standards
description: Enforce SEO best practices for all pages and components
filters:
  - type: file_extension
    pattern: "\\.tsx?$"
  - type: content
    pattern: "(?i)metadata|generateMetadata|NextSeo|<head>"

actions:
  - type: suggest
    message: |
      ## SEO Priority Checklist

      ### 1. Metadata Configuration
      - **Titles**: Unique, descriptive, under 60 characters. Format: `Page Title | Brand Name`.
      - **Descriptions**: Compelling summary, under 160 characters, includes keywords.
      - **Open Graph**: Always include `og:title`, `og:description`, `og:image`, `og:url`.
      - **Twitter Cards**: Include `twitter:card`, `twitter:creator`, `twitter:site`.
      - **Canonical URLs**: Always define a canonical URL to prevent duplicate content issues.

      ### 2. Semantic HTML
      - Use **one** `<h1>` per page (usually in the main content area).
      - Use correct heading hierarchy (`<h2>` follows `<h1>`, etc.).
      - Use semantic tags: `<header>`, `<main>`, `<footer>`, `<article>`, `<aside>`, `<nav>`.
      - Buttons are for actions, Links (`<a>`) are for navigation.

      ### 3. Image Optimization
      - Always use `next/image` for internal images.
      - **Alt Text**: Mandatory for all images. Descriptive for informative images, empty string (`alt=""`) for decorative.
      - **Dimensions**: Specify `width` and `height` or use `fill` with appropriate container aspect ratio to prevent CLS.
      - **Priority**: Use `priority` prop for LCP elements (images above the fold).

      ### 4. Performance & Core Web Vitals
      - **LCP (Largest Contentful Paint)**: Optimize hero images and text blocks.
      - **CLS (Cumulative Layout Shift)**: Reserve space for images, ads, and embeds.
      - **FID/INP (Interaction to Next Paint)**: Minimize main thread work, defer non-critical JS.

      ### 5. Structured Data (JSON-LD)
      - Implement Schema.org structured data for rich snippets (Product, Article, Organization, BreadcrumbList).
      - Use `next-seo` or Next.js built-in Metadata API for structured data injection.

      ### 6. URLs and Routing
      - Use descriptive, kebab-case URLs (e.g., `/services/web-development`).
      - Avoid deep nesting where possible.
      - Implement 301 redirects for changed URLs immediately.

      ### Example (Next.js App Router Metadata):
      ```typescript
      import type { Metadata } from 'next'

      export const metadata: Metadata = {
        title: 'About Us | My Company',
        description: 'Learn more about our mission and values.',
        openGraph: {
          title: 'About Us | My Company',
          description: 'Learn more about our mission and values.',
          url: 'https://example.com/about',
          siteName: 'My Company',
          images: [
            {
              url: 'https://example.com/og-about.png',
              width: 1200,
              height: 630,
            },
          ],
          locale: 'en_US',
          type: 'website',
        },
        alternates: {
          canonical: 'https://example.com/about',
        },
      }
      ```

metadata:
  priority: high
  version: 1.0
</rule>

<rule>
name: image_alt_text
description: Ensure all images have alt text
filters:
  - type: content
    pattern: "<Image"

actions:
  - type: reject
    conditions:
      - pattern: "<Image(?!.*alt=)"
        message: "All <Image> components must have an 'alt' prop. Use alt=\"\" for decorative images."

metadata:
  priority: critical
  version: 1.0
</rule>
